{{infobox book | name = Black Garden: Armenia and Azerbaijan Through Peace and War | translator = | image = Black Garden.jpg | caption = | author = [[Thomas de Waal]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | subject = [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]] | publisher = NYU Press | pub_date = 2003 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = 360 pages | isbn = 0-8147-6032-5 | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Black Garden: Armenia and Azerbaijan Through Peace and War''''' is a 2003 book by [[Thomas de Waal]], based on the study of [[Armenia]] and [[Azerbaijan]], two former [[Soviet]] republics, during the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas de Waal|url=http://belgradeforum.org/agenda/session2/119/Thomas+de+Waal.html|work=belgradeforum.org|publisher=Belgrade Security Forum|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref> It cuts between a careful reconstruction of the history of Nagorno Karabakh conflict since 1988 and on-the-spot reporting on its convoluted aftermath.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas de Waal presents supplemented version of his "Black Garden" book in Yerevan|url=http://www.mediamax.am/en/news/society/7675/|work=mediamax.am|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref>
Much of de Waal's analysis is concerned with the [[Caucasus]] region, focusing on the exercise of power on the Eurasian landmass in a post-Soviet environment.
