{{Infobox person | name = Daniyal Ametov | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|Month DD, YYYY}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] | other_names = | known_for = Member of NGO ''Advet'' | occupation = Activist }}
'''Daniyal Ametov''' is a [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] land-squatting activist in [[Ukraine]], and a member of the NGO ''Advet''.<ref>Valery Temnenko, Zeyneb Temnenko. [http://www.caei.com.ar/es/programas/cei/36.pdf Crimea's Three Basic Ethnic Components: A Pledge for Peace]. [[CAEI|Centro Argentino de Estudios Internacionales]], Programa CEI & Países Bálticos</ref>
The goal of Ametov and his organisation is to restore land rights in [[Crimea]] to the Tartar people, 200,000 of whom were forcibly deported to Central Asia in 1944 by [[Joseph Stalin]], under suspicion of being Nazi collaborators. The Crimean Tartars were allowed to return to their homeland towards the end of the Soviet era, but in many cases their lands had been redistributed in their absence. Some members of the community have taken to constructing temporary houses on land they wish to reclaim, without legal permission.<ref>Matthew Colin. [http://english.aljazeera.net/focus/2010/08/201087102453222638.html Crimean Tatars fear for future]. Al Jazeera English, August 8, 2010</ref>
Ametov was sentenced to four years in prison in October 2010 for intention infliction of trivial or medium bodily injury to a police officer by the Central District Court of [[Simferopol]]. This case was connected to an incident in 2007, where it was alleged that Ametov struck a police inspector in the face and caused a minor injury to his nose. The sentence was upheld by the Simferopol Appeal Court, but was reduced to three years by the Higher Specialized Court on Civil and Criminal Matters in March 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.milli-firka.org/content/DBAFJJCG/title/Amnesty-International8230/action/print | title = Amnesty International tried to defend the Daniyal Ametov: Letter to the General Prosecutor | author = Nicola Duckworth, Amnesty International | date = 26 January 2012 | accessdate = 28 April 2012}}</ref>
